('economics:2-6-production:match:a24cc2df', 'economics', 'economics:2-6-production', '2.6 Production', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Kaizen”?", "options": ["The total output of goods and services produced in a given time period", "Output per unit of input — a measure of the efficiency of the factors of production", "Costs that do not vary with the level of output, like rent and salaries", "Continuous small improvements suggested by workers at every level"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Kaizen” means: Continuous small improvements suggested by workers at every level"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:144f2b3b', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "A decrease in wages for construction workers would be most likely to...", "options": ["cause a shift in the demand curve for labour", "increase house prices", "lead to more construction workers being employed", "reduce the supply of houses"], "hint": "A lower wage is a movement ALONG the demand curve for labour, not a shift. At a lower wage, do firms hire more or fewer workers?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — lead to more construction workers being employed</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A fall in the wage is a movement DOWN the demand-for-labour curve: cheaper labour, so more workers are hired. It does not SHIFT the curve (A), and cheaper labour would tend to lower building costs, not raise house prices.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:daab29ef', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "Which of the following could lead to an increase in the DEMAND for engineers?", "options": ["Higher wages for engineers", "More engineering firms", "More engineers coming from abroad", "More engineering courses available at college"], "hint": "Demand for labour comes from FIRMS. Which option adds more employers who want to hire engineers? (The others change the supply.)", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — More engineering firms</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>More firms means more employers demanding engineers → demand for labour rises. Engineers from abroad or more college courses raise the SUPPLY of engineers; higher wages is a movement along the curve.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:6e6c49d5', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "What would most likely lead to a fall in the number of people applying for a new job?", "options": ["Decline in the size of the working population", "Decrease in demand for the product made", "Improvement in the working conditions", "Increase in the level of productivity"], "hint": "Applicants = the SUPPLY of labour. Which option means fewer people are available to work?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Decline in the size of the working population</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fewer working-age people means fewer applicants — a leftward shift in the supply of labour. Better working conditions would ATTRACT more applicants.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most of the candidates gave A as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:a78d698e', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "What is the BEST description of the role of the labour market?", "options": ["It allows workers able and willing to work to meet employers who are able and willing to offer a job", "It consists of the supply of labour by consumers and the demand for labour by firms", "It makes sure there is a competitive market for the skills offered by labour", "Negotiations take place between workers and employers to set the wage rate"], "hint": "''Best'' description — which captures the market bringing together willing workers and willing employers? (Careful: B says ''consumers'' supply labour, which is loose.)", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — It allows workers able and willing to work to meet employers able and willing to offer a job</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The labour market brings together willing workers and willing employers. B is imprecise (''consumers'' rather than households/workers).</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>Most candidates gave A as the correct response. It did not seem as if some candidates took notice of the word ''best''.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:611bdeae', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q5", "question": "What is meant by the labour market?", "options": ["The demand for labour by firms and the supply of labour by households", "The free movement of labour between different jobs", "The interaction between employers and workers about pay and conditions", "The working population excluding those retired or still in education"], "hint": "The core definition — who demands and who supplies?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — The demand for labour by firms and the supply of labour by households</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Firms demand, households supply. D describes the ''active labour force'', not the market itself.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A high percentage of candidates gave Option A as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:2dabd428', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "The diagram shows changes in the supply and demand for labour. The original equilibrium is at W. Where is equilibrium after an increase in the PRODUCTIVITY of labour?", "options": ["W", "X", "Y", "Z"], "caseStudy": "<img src=\"/images/economics/2-7-productivity-shift-wxyz-extracted.png\" alt=\"Diagram from the OCR exam paper: a labour market with supply S and demand D crossing at W, plus a second supply S1 and second demand D1, creating intersection points X, Y and Z around W\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:440px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "Higher productivity makes each worker more valuable → the DEMAND for labour shifts RIGHT (D to D1). Where does D1 cross the original supply S?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Y</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>More productive workers are worth more to firms, so the demand for labour shifts right from D to D1. The new equilibrium is where D1 meets the original supply S — point Y (a higher wage and more employed).</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>The correct response was Option B [Y in this layout]. However, a considerable percentage of candidates gave a response corresponding to the supply-shift point. Where candidates provided the intermediate point X, they were given one mark.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:3386b249', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "Sam''s monthly pay statement is shown. What is Sam''s monthly NET pay?", "options": ["£1,680", "£2,180", "£2,405", "£2,655"], "caseStudy": "<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:320px;margin:10px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Item</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">£</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Wage</td><td>2500</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Bonus</td><td>500</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Income tax</td><td>345</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">National Insurance</td><td>250</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Pension contributions</td><td>225</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "Gross = wage + bonus. Net = gross − all three deductions (income tax + NI + pension).", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2, Quantitative skills)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — £2,180</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Gross = £2,500 + £500 = £3,000. Deductions = £345 + £250 + £225 = £820. Net = £3,000 − £820 = £2,180.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>The correct response was Option B. Incorrect responses indicated a misunderstanding of how to calculate monthly net pay.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:dcadcc7d', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "What best explains why some suitable people will not apply for this job?", "options": ["The demand for labour is dependent on the demand for the product", "The price elasticity of demand for the advertised job is inelastic", "Their qualifications and experience are not in marketing", "This labour market lacks perfect mobility"], "caseStudy": "<p>A company advertised for a new marketing manager. Two essential requirements are that the person must have marketing experience and live within easy commuting distance. Pay will depend on the level of experience.</p>", "hint": "The two requirements (experience + living nearby) are exactly the barriers that stop willing workers taking a job. What concept covers that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — This labour market lacks perfect mobility</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The commuting-distance requirement is geographical immobility; the experience requirement is occupational immobility. Both are forms of imperfect labour mobility that stop suitable people applying.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>The correct response was Option D. Incorrect responses indicated a misunderstanding of factors affecting the way the labour market works.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:2eb515d9', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "What was Sundip''s GROSS income?", "options": ["£3,500", "£3,000", "£2,625", "£2,125"], "caseStudy": "<p>Sundip was paid a salary of £3,000. She also received a bonus of £500. Her employer deducted £875 to cover income tax and national insurance.</p>", "hint": "GROSS is before deductions — so ignore the £875. Add the salary and the bonus.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2, Quantitative skills)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — £3,500</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Gross = salary + bonus = £3,000 + £500 = £3,500. The £875 deduction only affects NET pay, not gross.</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>The correct response was Option A. While Option C was often selected, incorrect responses indicated a misunderstanding of how to correctly calculate gross income from the data provided.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:2dc42715', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "Net pay may be less than gross pay because of...", "options": ["government subsidies", "indirect taxes", "interest payments", "pension contributions"], "hint": "Which of these is a DEDUCTION taken straight out of a worker''s pay?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — pension contributions</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pension contributions are one of the three deductions (with income tax and NI) that make net pay lower than gross. Indirect taxes (like VAT) are on spending, not pay.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:4ee0e966', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q12", "question": "What might explain this difference in pay?", "options": ["Junior managers are in a trade union but senior managers are not", "Junior managers work more overtime than senior managers", "The senior manager''s work adds more value to the firm than the junior manager''s work", "The supply of senior managers is high relative to the demand for their services"], "caseStudy": "<p>The pay of a senior manager in a large business is £50,000 per year. A junior manager is paid £25,000 per year.</p>", "hint": "Higher pay usually reflects scarcer, higher-value skills. Which option says the senior manager is worth more to the firm?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — The senior manager''s work adds more value to the firm</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher-value, scarcer skills in strong demand and short supply command higher wages. D is backwards (high supply would LOWER pay).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:2b7d60a8', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q14", "question": "What is his annual NET pay?", "options": ["£1,500", "£2,500", "£18,000", "£24,000"], "caseStudy": "<p>John is paid in twelve monthly instalments. Each month he earns £2,000 in gross pay minus deductions for income tax of £500.</p>", "hint": "Monthly net = £2,000 − £500 = £1,500. Then multiply by 12 months.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2, Quantitative skills)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — £18,000</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Monthly net = £2,000 − £500 = £1,500. Annual net = £1,500 × 12 = £18,000. (£24,000 is annual GROSS.)</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A high percentage of candidates gave Option C as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:d70d0f35', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q16", "question": "The table shows the wage rate and employment level for two years in an industry. What would explain the change from Year 1 to Year 2?", "options": ["A decrease in the demand for labour", "A decrease in the supply of labour", "An increase in the demand for labour", "An increase in the supply of labour"], "caseStudy": "<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:440px;margin:10px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:center;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Year</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Wage rate (£ per week)</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Quantity of workers</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">1</td><td>440</td><td>4000</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">2</td><td>400</td><td>5000</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "Wage FELL (440→400) but employment ROSE (4000→5000). Which shift moves you DOWN the demand curve — lower wage, more employed?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2, Quantitative skills)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — An increase in the supply of labour</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The wage fell AND employment rose — that only happens when supply of labour shifts right, moving down the demand curve. A demand fall would cut BOTH wage and employment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:517ae18b', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q17", "question": "Her gross income per year is...", "options": ["£3,000", "£40,000", "£43,000", "£140,000"], "caseStudy": "<p>A chemist earns £40,000 a year. She has £100,000 in a bank account and the bank pays interest at 3% per year.</p>", "hint": "Gross income = ALL income before deductions: her salary PLUS the interest (3% of £100,000).", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2, Quantitative skills)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — £43,000</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Gross income = salary + savings interest = £40,000 + (3% × £100,000 = £3,000) = £43,000. Income is not only wages.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:2e77bf41', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q18", "question": "Which of the following is most likely to increase the wage rate of teachers in the UK?", "options": ["A fall in the number of children of school age", "A shortage of qualified teachers", "An increase in the number of qualified teachers coming to the UK from abroad", "An increase in the number of young people training to teach"], "hint": "A wage RISE needs either more demand or LESS supply of teachers. Which option makes teachers scarcer?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — A shortage of qualified teachers</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A shortage means the supply of teachers is low relative to demand → wages rise. The other three raise supply (teachers from abroad, more trainees) or cut demand (fewer children), lowering wages.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:exam:e364f0cf', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q19", "question": "A firm''s labour productivity will have increased when...", "options": ["the level of output and the labour force both decrease by 50%", "the level of output and the labour force both increase by 100%", "the level of output increases by 100% as the labour force increases by 80%", "the level of output increases by 100% as the labour force increases by 120%"], "hint": "Productivity = output per worker. It rises only when output grows FASTER than the workforce.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — output increases 100% while the labour force increases 80%</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Output per worker rises only if output grows faster than the workforce (100% vs 80%). Equal growth (B) leaves productivity unchanged; slower output growth (D) lowers it.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:b2c0953d', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "In the labour market, the demand for labour comes from...", "options": ["Firms (employers)", "The government only", "Households (workers)", "Trade unions"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Firms demand labour; households supply it — the reverse of a goods market. This reversal is the topic''s biggest trap."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:cf4ea5a7', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A firm''s demand for workers depends on the demand for the product they make. This is called...", "options": ["Excess demand", "Composite demand", "Derived demand", "Effective demand"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Demand for labour is DERIVED from demand for the good/service it produces — demand for baristas derives from demand for coffee."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:b527c925', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A decrease in wages for construction workers is most likely to...", "options": ["Lead to more construction workers being employed", "Cause the demand curve for labour to shift", "Increase house prices", "Reduce the supply of houses"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A lower wage is a movement DOWN the demand curve for labour — cheaper labour, so firms hire more workers."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:e2b80ddd', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which would increase the DEMAND for engineers?", "options": ["Higher wages for engineers", "More engineering firms opening", "More engineers coming from abroad", "More engineering courses at college"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "More firms means more employers wanting engineers → demand rises. The other options raise the SUPPLY of engineers, or move along the curve."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:510cba60', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Positive net migration into a country''s workforce shifts the...", "options": ["Supply of labour to the left", "Supply of labour to the right, lowering wages", "Demand for labour to the right, raising wages", "Demand for labour to the left"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "More workers available = supply of labour shifts right, pushing the equilibrium wage down but employment up."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:023d6b42', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which is most likely to INCREASE the wage rate of teachers?", "options": ["A fall in the number of school-age children", "More young people training to teach", "More qualified teachers arriving from abroad", "A shortage of qualified teachers"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "A shortage means supply of teachers is low relative to demand → wages rise. The other three raise supply or cut demand, lowering wages."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:e1fd2186', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Gross pay differs from net pay because net pay is calculated...", "options": ["By adding bonuses to gross pay", "Before any deductions", "After deductions like income tax, NI and pension", "By adding savings interest"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Net (take-home) pay = gross pay MINUS deductions. Gross is before deductions."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:971057ca', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Sam earns £2,500 wage + £500 bonus. Deductions: income tax £345, NI £250, pension £225. Net pay is...", "options": ["£1,680", "£2,655", "£3,000", "£2,180"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Gross = £2,500 + £500 = £3,000. Deductions = £345 + £250 + £225 = £820. Net = £3,000 − £820 = £2,180."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:1d6665cb', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A senior manager earns far more than a junior manager. The best explanation is that...", "options": ["The senior avoids trade unions", "The supply of senior managers is high", "The junior works more overtime", "The senior''s work adds more value to the firm"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Scarcer, higher-value skills in strong demand and short supply command higher wages — the value-added explanation."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:mcq:7689048f', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A firm''s labour productivity has increased when...", "options": ["Output and labour force both rise 100%", "Output rises 100% while the labour force rises 80%", "Output rises 100% while the labour force rises 120%", "Output and labour force both fall 50%"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Productivity = output per worker. If output grows FASTER than the workforce (100% vs 80%), output per worker rises. Equal growth means no change; slower means a fall."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:7d80026a', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "In the labour market, households demand labour and firms supply it."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The reverse — FIRMS demand labour (they hire), HOUSEHOLDS supply it (they work). This is the topic''s most common error."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:56b91511', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Demand for labour is a derived demand."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "It depends on demand for the good or service the workers produce — demand for construction workers derives from demand for houses."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:ca25363f', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "An increase in the supply of labour raises the equilibrium wage."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "More workers pushes the wage DOWN (and employment up) — you move down the demand curve. It''s a LEFT shift of supply that raises wages."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:1d165c36', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Wages are income to workers but a cost to firms."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "The same wage is a reward to the household and a cost of production to the employer — which is why the two sides pull in opposite directions."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:1a1e6367', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A shortage of qualified nurses will tend to lower nurses'' wages."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A shortage means supply is low relative to demand, so wages RISE. Scarcity of a skill pushes its wage up."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:60cf4abf', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Gross pay is your take-home pay after deductions."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "That''s NET pay. Gross pay is total earnings BEFORE deductions (the examiner-critical word)."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:0bf51861', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Moving into a higher income-tax band means all your income is taxed at the higher rate."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Only the slice ABOVE the threshold is taxed at the higher rate. Earning more always leaves you with more after tax."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tf:c203969e', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Occupational immobility is when workers cannot move jobs because their skills don''t transfer."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "A redundant miner can''t instantly become a programmer. Geographical immobility is the different one — being unable/unwilling to relocate."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:learn:82869553', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What the labour market is — and how it works", "reading": "<p><strong>The labour market is where firms (employers) DEMAND labour and households (workers) SUPPLY it</strong> — it works like any other market, except the thing being traded is workers'' time and skill. The <strong>wage rate is the price of labour</strong>, set by the interaction of demand and supply.</p>\n<h4>The key reversal — learn this cold</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>DEMAND for labour comes from FIRMS</strong> (employers who want to hire).</li>\n<li><strong>SUPPLY of labour comes from WORKERS / households</strong> (people offering themselves for work).</li>\n<li>This is the OPPOSITE way round from a goods market, where households demand and firms supply — the reversal is the single most common thing students get wrong.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Wages are income to workers, a COST to firms</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The same wage is a reward to the household but a cost of production to the employer — which is why firms want it low and workers want it high.</li>\n<li><strong>Wage</strong> = paid per hour, usually weekly (more common in lower-skilled jobs). <strong>Salary</strong> = a yearly amount, usually paid monthly (professional roles).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Derived demand</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A firm''s demand for workers is a <strong>derived demand</strong> — it depends on demand for the good or service the labour produces. Demand for baristas comes from demand for coffee; demand for construction workers from demand for houses.</li>\n<li>So if the product sells more, the firm needs more workers — the whole factor market and product market are interdependent.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Two other players besides market forces</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Government</strong> — sets the National Minimum Wage and National Living Wage (the least an employer may legally pay).</li>\n<li><strong>Trade unions</strong> — represent workers, using collective bargaining to push for higher pay and better conditions.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "In the labour market, who DEMANDS labour and who SUPPLIES it?", "options": ["Firms demand labour; households supply it", "Trade unions demand labour", "Households demand labour; firms supply it", "The government demands and supplies labour"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The reversal from goods markets: firms are the buyers (employers) and workers/households are the sellers. Getting this backwards is the classic error."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:learn:feddf14f', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "The determination of wages — supply and demand shifts", "reading": "<p>The <strong>equilibrium wage</strong> is where the supply of labour equals the demand for labour. Like any price, wages trend towards equilibrium — excess supply pulls wages down, excess demand pushes them up. Every wage question comes down to shifting a curve and reading off BOTH the new wage and the new employment level.</p>\n<h4>The four outcomes — always give wage AND quantity</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Demand for labour RIGHT</strong> (a growing firm/industry) → higher wage, more employed.</li>\n<li><strong>Demand for labour LEFT</strong> (recession, declining industry, low profits) → lower wage, fewer employed.</li>\n<li><strong>Supply of labour RIGHT</strong> (migration, more trained workers) → lower wage, more employed.</li>\n<li><strong>Supply of labour LEFT</strong> (skill shortage, workforce shrinking) → higher wage, fewer employed.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What shifts DEMAND for labour</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>More demand for the firm''s product (derived demand); a growing/strong economy; higher firm profits reinvested in expansion; more productive workers (each worker is worth more).</li>\n<li>Falls when: recession, a declining industry, low profits, or rising wages making labour less efficient to use.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What shifts SUPPLY of labour</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher wage rates draw more people in; positive net migration; a growing working-age population; better working conditions/job security; flexible and home working; rising education and qualifications (more SKILLED supply).</li>\n<li>Falls when: wages drop, or the workforce shrinks (more retiring than entering, negative net migration).</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The exam-critical habit:</strong> always LABEL the vertical axis \"Wages\" (or \"Price of labour\") — an unlabelled axis fails to show it is a labour market and caps your marks.</p>", "question": "Positive net migration increases the number of workers. What happens to the equilibrium wage and employment?", "options": ["Demand for labour shifts right → higher wage", "Supply shifts left → higher wage", "Nothing changes", "Supply of labour shifts right → lower wage, more employed"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "More workers = supply of labour shifts right, moving down the demand curve: the wage falls but more people are employed. Always state BOTH effects."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:learn:f5b730ee', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Why wages differ between jobs", "reading": "<p>A senior manager earns more than a junior not simply because they \"work harder\" — it comes down to the demand for and supply of that specific skill, and how elastic each is. <strong>Wage differentials</strong> are the differences in pay workers get for their services.</p>\n<h4>The rule: high demand + low supply = high wage</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Jobs needing scarce, hard-to-acquire skills (surgeons, CEOs) have <strong>inelastic, limited supply</strong> and high demand → HIGH wages, but FEW people employed.</li>\n<li>Jobs needing few skills that many people can do have <strong>elastic, plentiful supply</strong> → LOW wages, but MANY people employed.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Factors that widen wage differences</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Skills, qualifications and experience</strong> — scarcer skills command more. Workers build their <strong>human capital</strong> over a lifetime to raise their value.</li>\n<li><strong>Risk / unpleasantness</strong> — dangerous or unpleasant jobs may pay a premium.</li>\n<li><strong>Supply of qualified workers</strong> — a shortage (nurses, HGV drivers) pushes wages up; a surplus pushes them down.</li>\n<li><strong>Trade unions</strong> — collective bargaining can lift members'' pay above the individual rate.</li>\n<li><strong>Government</strong> — the minimum/living wage sets a floor; anti-discrimination law also affects wage-setting.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The value-added point (a real MCQ)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A senior manager is often paid more because their work <strong>adds more value to the firm</strong> — higher productivity/marginal value means the employer will pay more to keep them.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why is a senior manager (£50,000) usually paid more than a junior manager (£25,000)?", "options": ["Senior managers are all in trade unions", "The senior manager''s work adds more value to the firm", "The supply of senior managers is very high", "Junior managers work more overtime"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Higher-value, scarcer skills in high demand and low supply command higher wages. A real exam MCQ — ''adds more value'' is the answer."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:learn:1e6da9ba', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Labour immobility, and gross vs net pay", "reading": "<p>The labour market lacks <strong>perfect mobility</strong> — workers often can''t just switch jobs, even when vacancies exist. And pay comes in two forms every exam tests: gross and net.</p>\n<h4>Two types of immobility</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Occupational immobility</strong> — skills don''t transfer. A redundant miner can''t instantly become a computer programmer; their skill set is too specific.</li>\n<li><strong>Geographical immobility</strong> — unwilling or unable to move: family ties, owning property, the cost of relocating to an area they can''t afford.</li>\n<li>Also: personal preferences and a lack of information about vacancies (easing with online job adverts). This is why some suitable people won''t apply for a job — a real MCQ.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Gross pay vs net pay — learn the definitions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Gross pay</strong> — total earnings BEFORE any deductions (includes bonuses and overtime). The key word examiners want is \"before deductions\".</li>\n<li><strong>Net pay</strong> (take-home pay) — what''s left AFTER deductions.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The three deductions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Income tax</strong> — a STATUTORY deduction (you must pay). Charged only on income above the tax-free threshold (~£12,570). Progressive: higher earners pay a higher % — but ONLY on the slice above each threshold.</li>\n<li><strong>National Insurance</strong> — also statutory; paid by BOTH workers and employers to fund social benefits.</li>\n<li><strong>Pension contributions</strong> — usually a VOLUNTARY deduction, paid into a fund you access at retirement (as a lump sum or an annuity).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The progressive-tax misconception</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Moving into a higher tax band does NOT tax all your income at the higher rate — only the portion above the threshold. Earning more always leaves you with more after tax. Show your working on these.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Gross income also includes non-wage income</strong> — e.g. interest on savings. A chemist earning £40,000 with £100,000 in the bank at 3% has a gross income of £43,000 (£40,000 + £3,000 interest).</p>", "question": "What is ''gross pay''?", "options": ["Take-home pay after deductions", "Pay after income tax but before National Insurance", "Total earnings before any deductions", "Only the bonus part of pay"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Gross = before deductions (the examiner-critical word). Net = take-home after income tax, NI and pension come out."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:misc:a2473fa6', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Workers demand labour and firms supply it, like a normal market.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The labour market is the MIRROR IMAGE of a goods market: FIRMS demand labour (they are the buyers/employers) and HOUSEHOLDS supply it (they are the sellers/workers). The wage is the price. Get this backwards and every labour diagram comes out wrong — a rise in demand for labour (from firms wanting more workers) raises the wage, while a rise in supply of labour (more workers available) lowers it. Whenever you read a labour question, first pin down which side each actor is on: an employer story is a DEMAND story; a workers/migration/training story is a SUPPLY story.</p>", "question": "More engineering FIRMS open. In the market for engineers, this shifts...", "options": ["Supply of labour right", "Demand for labour right (firms want more engineers)", "Supply of labour left", "Demand for labour left"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Firms are the demanders. More firms = more demand for engineers = higher wages. (More engineering COURSES would shift supply instead.)"}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:misc:8c4173ae', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"On a labour diagram I''ll just draw supply and demand crossing.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Two things sink labour diagrams in real papers. First, LABEL THE VERTICAL AXIS ''Wages'' (or ''Price of labour'') — the examiner report on the Mia question said candidates who left the Y-axis unlabelled couldn''t show it was a labour market and lost marks. Second, always read off BOTH effects: a shift changes the wage AND the level of employment. ''Supply of workers like Mia rose, so the wage fell from w to w1 and employment rose from q to q1'' scores; ''wages fell'' alone does not. And the analysis must be LINKED to the diagram — an unlinked diagram caps you at Level 2 (4/6).</p>", "question": "What must the vertical axis of a labour-market diagram be labelled?", "options": ["Price", "Profit", "Quantity", "Wages (or Price of labour)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Labelling it ''Wages'' is what shows it''s a LABOUR market — the real mark scheme docked candidates who left it as a generic ''Price''."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:misc:3a8ef5aa', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Wages are paid out of profits, so low profits mean low wages directly.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The real ''low business profits on wages'' question flagged this exact misconception. Wages are NOT paid out of profit — they are a cost of production, paid before profit is even calculated. The correct chain works through the LABOUR DIAGRAM: low profits deter firms from investing and expanding, so the DEMAND for labour falls (D to D1), which lowers both the wage (w to w1) and employment (q to q1). Route it through derived demand and a leftward demand-for-labour shift, not a direct ''profit pays wages'' link.</p>", "question": "How do low business profits lower wages?", "options": ["Firms invest/expand less, so demand for labour falls, pulling wages down", "Workers refuse to work", "The government cuts wages", "Wages are paid directly out of profit"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The link is through DEMAND for labour: low profits → less expansion → demand for labour shifts left → lower wage and employment."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:misc:70c99cb7', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Productivity means producing more — an economy has more products.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The real ''importance of productivity'' evaluation exposed this: weaker answers treated productivity as just ''more production'', missing the whole point. Productivity is output PER worker (efficiency), and its power is that it CUTS AVERAGE COSTS. Lower unit costs → lower prices → greater international competitiveness → more exports, better balance of trade, higher profits and wages, and economic growth. The context matters too: the extract says UK productivity is 15% below its main competitors and 25% below Germany, so raising it is important for closing that gap. Always route productivity through falling average costs, not just ''more output''.</p>", "question": "Why does higher productivity make an economy more competitive?", "options": ["It reduces the workforce", "It raises taxes", "It simply means more products exist", "It lowers average costs, so firms can charge lower prices"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Output per worker up = cost per unit down = lower prices and more exports. ''More products'' misses the average-cost mechanism entirely."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:misc:d54c11e7', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Low UK wage increases hurt Crotay by lowering their workers'' morale.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The real Crotay question gave 0 marks to answers about worker morale or productivity — it asked about the PRODUCT market. The chain runs the other way: low wage increases across the UK mean consumers have less disposable income, so they buy fewer products — including Crotay''s specialist car tyres. Fewer sales damages Crotay''s performance in the product market. This is the interdependence of factor and product markets: what workers earn (factor market) determines what they can spend (product market). Follow low pay → low disposable income → lower demand for the firm''s product.</p>", "question": "How do low UK wage increases damage Crotay''s PRODUCT-market performance?", "options": ["Crotay''s productivity falls", "Crotay''s own workers become demotivated", "Crotay pays more tax", "Consumers have less income, so buy fewer of Crotay''s tyres"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Low pay across the economy → less consumer spending → lower demand for Crotay''s product. Morale/productivity answers scored 0."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:misc:0a877dfc', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Mia is a factor of production, so that''s why she''s in a factor market.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Half-right scored only 1 mark on the real question. Yes, labour is a factor of production — but you must LINK it: the factor market is where the services of factors of production are bought and sold, and Mia, looking for her first job, is SELLING HER LABOUR while a firm is BUYING it. That transaction — Mia supplying labour, an employer demanding it — is what makes her part of the factor market. Just listing the factors of production, or describing the product market, scored 0. Always finish the chain: factor market = buying/selling of labour, and Mia is the seller.</p>", "question": "Why is Mia, job-hunting, part of the FACTOR market?", "options": ["She is a consumer", "Labour is one of the four factors of production", "She is selling her labour (a factor of production) to an employer who is buying it", "She will buy products with her wages"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The factor market is where labour is bought and sold — Mia is the SELLER of her labour. Just naming labour as a factor was only 1 mark."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tips:6c53921e', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "diagrams — Labour-market diagrams: label the axis, read both effects", "reading": "<p>Three of this paper''s 6-markers are labour supply-and-demand diagrams (SSA gross pay, low profits on wages, Mia''s lower earnings). The examiners keep repeating two failures:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Label the vertical axis ''Wages''</strong> (or ''Price of labour''). Candidates who drew a perfect diagram but left it as generic ''Price'' couldn''t show it was a labour market — and lost marks.</li>\n<li><strong>Read off wage AND employment</strong>: name the shift (which curve, which way), then both the new wage (w→w1) and the new quantity of labour (q→q1).</li>\n<li><strong>Link the words to the diagram</strong> — refer to it explicitly (''as the diagram shows, demand falls from D to D1''). Unlinked diagrams are capped at Level 2 (4/6), and the whole answer is capped at 4/6 with no correct diagram.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The three signature shifts</h4>\n<p>SSA competition → demand for skilled labour RIGHT + inelastic supply = big wage rise, small quantity change. Low profits → demand for labour LEFT = wage and employment fall. Mia → supply of new graduates RIGHT (or demand LEFT) = wage falls.</p>", "question": "You draw a correct labour diagram but forget to label the Y-axis ''Wages''. The examiner report says you...", "options": ["Get bonus marks for the diagram", "Still get full marks", "Get 6/6 automatically", "Lose marks — the diagram doesn''t show it''s a labour market"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The Mia mark scheme is explicit: an unlabelled axis fails to show a LABOUR market. Label it Wages or Price of labour every time."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tips:89be946a', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "calculation — Pay calculations: gross, net, and what counts as income", "reading": "<p>This topic is calculation-heavy. The formulas are simple; the marks go on reading the question:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Net pay</strong> = gross (wage + bonus) − ALL deductions. Sam: (£2,500+£500) − (£345+£250+£225) = £2,180.</li>\n<li><strong>Gross income includes non-wage income</strong>: the chemist''s £40,000 salary + 3% of £100,000 savings = £43,000. Don''t forget interest, rent or bonuses.</li>\n<li><strong>Gross before net</strong>: Sundip''s £3,000 + £500 bonus = £3,500 gross (the £875 deduction is irrelevant to GROSS).</li>\n<li><strong>Annual from monthly</strong>: John''s (£2,000 − £500) × 12 = £18,000 net a year.</li>\n<li><strong>Mia''s package</strong>: £30,000 + (£200 × 12) + 10% of £30,000 = £35,400 — show every step so the Own Figure Rule can rescue a slip.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A chemist earns £40,000 and has £100,000 in savings paying 3% interest. Her gross income is...", "options": ["£140,000", "£40,000", "£3,000", "£43,000"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Gross income = salary + savings interest = £40,000 + (3% × £100,000 = £3,000) = £43,000. Income isn''t only wages."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tips:5eadd3fa', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "data — Data questions: describe the TREND, not the numbers", "reading": "<p>The Crotay wage-increases chart is a rate-of-change chart — and (like the house-price traps in 2.4) it catches candidates out.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>State the pattern</strong>: wages rose 0.5%, FELL in 2014 (to −1%), then rose at an increasing rate up to 2%. Overall, wages rose across the period.</li>\n<li><strong>Watch the axis</strong>: the bars show the RATE at which wages increased, not the wage level. A negative bar (2014) is a real fall; a smaller positive bar is slower growth, not a fall.</li>\n<li><strong>Don''t just list the numbers</strong>: ''no marks for simply repeating the data'' — you must describe direction and change.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The productivity-comparison version</h4>\n<p>For the Oxbria chart, COMPARE: the UK is above the Western Europe average and above France and Germany, but only 4th of 8, and the three above it are much smaller economies. Comparison, not recitation.</p>", "question": "The Crotay chart shows a bar of −1% in 2014 and +2% in 2018. Between 2014 and 2018, wage increases...", "options": ["Went from a fall to rising at an increasing rate", "Stayed the same", "Were always negative", "Fell every year"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "2014 is a genuine fall (negative bar); after that the rate of increase climbs to 2%. Describe the pattern, don''t just quote figures."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:tips:1761f71d', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — Evaluate: route productivity through average costs, TR through TC", "reading": "<p>Two big Evaluates recur on this paper, each with a trap the examiners named:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>''Importance of productivity for the UK economy''</strong> — the winning route is productivity → lower AVERAGE COSTS → competitiveness → exports, growth, higher wages/profits. Weaker answers treated productivity as just ''more output'' and stalled. Use the extract: UK is 15% below competitors, 25% below Germany. Weigh a downside (capital replacing labour → unemployment; environmental strain).</li>\n<li><strong>''Extent to which more revenue means more profit''</strong> — start from profit = TR − TC. More TR only means more profit if TR rises FASTER than costs. The official Misconception box: revenue and profit are NOT the same.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Always meet the frame</h4>\n<p>''The extent to which'' and ''the importance of'' need a judgement that answers exactly that — ''Overall, productivity is very important for the UK because it drives the competitiveness the economy currently lacks, though the gains depend on how it is achieved.''</p>", "question": "For ''evaluate the importance of productivity'', the mechanism that earns the marks is productivity lowering...", "options": ["Average costs, raising competitiveness", "Total output only", "The workforce size", "Tax rates"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The examiner report: weaker answers said ''more output'' and missed the fall in AVERAGE costs that drives lower prices, exports and growth."}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:fib:ba526fed', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "In the labour market, ___B1___ demand labour and ___B2___ supply it — the reverse of a goods market.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["firms", "move", "product", "rises"], "B2": ["households", "product", "immobility", "supply"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "firms", "B2": "households"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:fib:c16a5624', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "A firm''s demand for workers is a ___B1___ demand, because it depends on the demand for the ___B2___ the labour makes.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["demand", "derived", "rises", "move"], "B2": ["rises", "product", "immobility", "households"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "derived", "B2": "product"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:fib:76dbcfe4', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "When the supply of labour shifts right, the equilibrium wage ___B1___ but the number employed ___B2___.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["supply", "falls", "gross", "firms"], "B2": ["inelastic", "rises", "net", "demand"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "falls", "B2": "rises"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:fib:f2fd7c13', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "Scarce, skilled workers have an ___B1___ supply, so they earn ___B2___ wages than workers whose skills many people have.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["rises", "inelastic", "supply", "immobility"], "B2": ["derived", "gross", "rises", "higher"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "inelastic", "B2": "higher"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:fib:d5996710', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "___B1___ pay is total earnings before deductions; ___B2___ pay is take-home pay after income tax, NI and pension are removed.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["demand", "higher", "move", "gross"], "B2": ["net", "rises", "demand", "higher"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "gross", "B2": "net"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:fib:761197d8', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "Occupational ___B1___ means a worker''s skills do not transfer to a new job; geographical immobility means they cannot or will not ___B2___.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["immobility", "supply", "households", "gross"], "B2": ["higher", "move", "firms", "net"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "immobility", "B2": "move"}}'::jsonb),
('economics:2-7-the-labour-market:match:f699acc2', 'economics', 'economics:2-7-the-labour-market', '2.7 The Labour Market', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Labour market”?", "options": ["The price of labour, set by the demand for and supply of workers", "Demand for labour that comes from demand for the product it makes", "Where firms demand labour and households supply it, setting the wage rate", "The wage where the supply of labour equals the demand for labour"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Labour market” means: Where firms demand labour and households supply it, setting the wage rate"}'::jsonb)
